Name: Former Schoolhouse No. 6/School No. 22/The Kline Schoolhouse
Notes: Site of the first schoolhouse in Cayuga Heights, the original house was built in the early- to mid-1800s, on land from the Cradit farm family. Today, evidence of the house's original use can be seen in the two doors that flank the chimney--one entrance for girls; one for boys. The schoolhouse bell remains in the office, a reminder of schooldays past. (Village History, Notable Architecture)
Sir Ian Axford lived here (1965-67), one of the greatest figures in space and astrophysical plasma research.

Name: Formerly Hanshaw House
Notes: The Hanshaw family gave its name to Hanshaw Road. James Hanshaw purchased a 92-acre lot from Jacob and Mary Cradit in 1830. The Hanshaw farm lot ran north and south of Hanshaw Road at the intersection of today’s Pleasant Grove Road, from about present-day Texas Lane in the north and south along Pleasant Grove Road. Christine Hanshaw, James’s widow, and their children and their spouses sold the property in 1871 to Jesse Manning for $9,500. The house at 1011 Hanshaw Road, on the Hanshaw’s lot, was built in 1870, according to the Tompkins County Assessment page.
Home of Cayuga Heights Mayor, Walter Lynn, 1970-2000. Impressive gardens can be seen from the street. (Natural Environment)

1978-83 home of African American Civil Rights Leader, Makaza Kumanyika, formerly known as Herbert Callender. Spetember 11 is Makaza Kumanyika Day in New Jersey. Wife, Shiriki Kumanyika, was an epidemiologist at Cornell. Also home to Cayuga Heights school teacher, Constance Cougherty 1969-73.

1939 home of Magdalen Flexner, U.S. Ambassador in Europe, Consul General in France, her husband, William W. Flexner, mathemetician. Also home to Nobel Prize winner, Clinton Rossiter, as well as Robert "Jack" Lambert, Cornell professor of freehand drawing. See a gallery of his work on The History Project website or in person at Marcham Hall. (Major Award Winners,Artists, Notable Women)
Home of physicist and Nobel Prize winner Peter Debye from 1951 to 1976. Debye is buried nearby at Pleasant Grove Cemetery. (Major Award Winners)

Relatively inexpensive "Kit houses," assembled from standardized parts and designs, became an affordable alternative to architect-designed homes as the demand for housing on the part of middle class buyers increased in the 1930s and thereafter. All the oak woodwork and floors, roofing, and brass fittings of 104 Klinewoods and its twin at 203 East Upland Road were shipped by the Bennett Company, whose work is archived at the North Tonawanda Historical Society Museum. Other kit houses in the Arts and Crafts, Bungalow, and Colonial Revival styles are scattered in the Village awaiting identification and their stories. Cornell physics professor Guy Grantham and his wife were the first owners of this house. Later home to school teacher, Mary V. Russell, 1965-79. (Notable Architecture)
Home to Pulitzer Prize and National Humanities Medal winner David Brion Davis (1959-71), a historian and leading authority on the history of slavery and abolition. (Major Award Winners)

Former site of the farm belonging to Thompson and Caroline Manning, whose daughter Carrie Manning wrote daily diary entries in 1869. The diary is available in print and digital format. (Farmhouses)

Name: Greystone; Sigma Chi Fraternity
Notes:
Greystone" is known for its second owners, Irene Castle, dancer and silent film star, and Robert E. Treman, scion of the prominent family in Ithaca's early business community. In 1918, the home was featured in the Wharton Studios film, A Romance in the Air. Irene was often photographed at Greystone in such magazines as Vanity Fair, Vogue, and Town and Country. Having been the scene of a true "Roaring Twenties" lifestyle, the lavish mansion was sold in 1924 to Cornell's Sigma Chi fraternity.

Name: HiddenHome
Notes:
Helen Binkerd Young, the only woman  in the 1900 Cornell architecture graduating class, began teaching home design in the Home Economics Department in 1910. Unwelcome by society as an architecture professor, she did succeed in designing several homes in Cayuga Heights, among them, her own house, "Hiddenhome," which she designed in collaboration with her husband, architect George Young.
Societal and institutional obstacles to women in the practice of architecture impeded her career. In 1910, she listed herself in the U.S. Census as having "no occupation." In 1930, the 19th Amendment having been passed ten years earlier, she listed "architect." (Notable Architecture, Notable Women)

Charles Newman--son of Cayuga Heights developer Jared T. Newman--and his wife Marion wanted a smaller house than those Charles had grown up in, recognizing that they could not afford the wealthy lifestyle of his parents. Times were changing; the Depression was coming. Marion would do much of the housework, so theirs was reputedly the first village house built without a maid's room. 
 
 Jared Newman was much impressed with his son and daughter-in-law's home, designed by Ithaca architect LeRoy Burnham, so much so that he turned his attention to the building of smaller homes a bit farther north in the Village from the original section where his own grand house stood at the intersection of Highland Road and The Parkway. Smaller and cheaper housing, he hoped, would not mean "Cheap John" designs; his solution was the development he called Klinewoods, beginning in 1932. (Notable Architecture, Village History)

Name: former "Hitchcock Hall"
Notes:
In 1920, Jared Newman transferred land on which Union Free School District No. 6 was built in 1924 at the intersection of Upland, Highland, and Hanshaw Roads, then known as Cayuga Circle where the old trolley line stopped. As Newman intended, the central location added to the attraction of Cayuga Heights for families with children. Named for its beloved first principal, Miss Martha Hitchcock, Hitchcock Hall was the forerunner of the Cayuga Heights Elementary School. It was a beautiful, rambling Tudor-style building in a park-like setting. Sadly, the era of urban renewal brought its demolition and replacement by the Ithaca City School District in 1968 with the current, much more generic building, which has been added on to since. 
 
 In 1980, enrollment decline caused the Ithaca City School District to close the school. Disappointed villagers responded with the formation of a Cayuga Heights Community Association under the leadership of Betty Matyas, who lived next door to the school. Tenants were found, including a Montessori school, to keep the building viable, and when enrollments climbed back up, the school was reopened in 1988 for both village children and those bussed from West Hill. In 1995, the large number of older adults who sold their homes and moved to Kendal at Ithaca flooded the real estate market with houses that young families proved eager to purchase, and so, once again the school was bursting at the seams. (Garden, Public Sites, Playground)
Robert and Martha Peach were the original owners of this rambling Ranch-style home, designed by Erma Cicchetti. Pilot Robert Peach managed Robinson Airlines, which later became Mohawk Airlines.

Name: Hulburt House; Ecology House; Former Cornell Residential Club
Notes: Dormitory, Public Sites

In 1913, Jane McKelway (1892-1993) graduated from Cornell University and taught English and French at the Cascadilla School. In 1919, she purchased a triangular lot in the White Park section of Cayuga Heights and moved into the newly built home in 1921 with her husband, civil engineering professor Leonard C. Urquhart (1886-1960), and their two-year-old son Edmund. The family lived in the home for only two years. In 1923, the Urquharts sold the home to Paul M. Lincoln, who had been appointed director of Cornell's electrical engineering department (see 520 Cayuga Heights Road).

Name: former, Robert Bush Farmhouse
Notes: Robert Bush bought 57 ½ acres from Israel and Anna Shafer in 1834. The farmhouse was built in the same year.  Robert and Sally (Manning) Bush's son Isaac Bush took over the property in 1877. In 1879, the farm produced butter, wool, corn, oats, wheat, and potatoes. In 1916 the house was sold by Jared and Jane Newman to David C. Gillespie, professor of mathematics at Cornell. The Gillespies installed an extensive perennial garden designed in 1934 by landscape architect Edward Lawson. Much of the original garden has been maintained to this day. (Notable Architecture)
From 1942-1944 the home of physicist and Nobel Prize winner Peter Debye from 1951 to 1976. Debye is buried nearby at Pleasant Grove Cemetery. (Major Award Winners)

Former home of Cayuga Heights mayor, Frederick Marcham. Though built during the Great Depression, the house is so solid, it still retains its structural integrity, and was built with extra thick walls. While millions lost their jobs and their money in the Crash, Cornell faculty salaries were cut only 6-10%, leaving them with the means to hire the available labor to continue to build comfortable homes. 
 
 Initially, garages in the Heights were required to face away from the street, however, people often did not even have a car. Since that time, most garages have been changed to face the street, and many have been expanded to fit two cars and now, recycling bins. 
 
 Of living in this area in the 1930s, Marcham writes in his account, "Memories of Cayuga Heights, N.Y.," of a "typical Cayuga Heights Street": "My wife and I had chosen a place in Oak Hill Road that would allow our children a half mile walk to school and give me a one mile walk to the Cornell campus. For the walk I had friends; two of my neighbors joined me in walking, and one of them, like myself, owned no car....Their wives walked down Oak Hill Road westward to Highland Road and then south to the bus stop on Thurston Avenue. For a time, in the 1930s, milkmen and men who delivered ice, and the leading grocers in Ithaca, allowed us to order goods and brought them to us and to other persons around the City of Ithaca. If you were sick you would not go to the doctor; he or she came to you, the doctor with the little black bag. And once or twice a year the coalman came and poured tons of coal down a chute into your cellar." (Village History)

Name: Cradit-Moore House
Notes:
The Cradit-Moore House represents a successful recent effort at preserving our local heritage. The earliest section of the home, its northern wing (1817), was constructed by Isaac Cradit. It possesses many Greek Revival characteristics such as pilasters, a cornice line with full entablature, a pediment-shaped door surround and elaborate window molding. 
 
 Around 1860-61, the southern wing was added when it was sold to Peter Kline, who owned much farmland in the area. 
 The house was bought by Dr. and Mrs. Norman Moore in 1938 and underwent many changes. Dr. Moore was the first Director of Cornell University’s health care system. In 1948 the house was sold to Cornell with the Moores retaining lifetime residency.
 
 About fifteen years ago, Cornell’s expansion blueprint for the North Campus included plans to demolish the building, and Historic Ithaca stepped in to save the almost 200-year-old structure. In 2000, the house was moved about three-tenths of a mile north of its original location at 128 Pleasant Grove Road to its current location. 
(Notable Architecture)
Notable Architecture

Name: Cayuga Heights Fire Department
Notes:
The home of the Village's all-volunteer fire department, the station was named to honor the late mayor Ron Anderson because of his leadership during its design and construction. The Department's founding membership in 1955 was drawn from local workers and from Cornell faculty. Today, an innovative "bunker" program allows some members, usually Cornell or Ithaca College students, to live in second floor dormitory rooms rent-free in exchange for firefighting and emergency medical treatment services. This unique arrangement is one way the Department is able to maintain the fastest response time among area volunteer departments, two to three minutes. 
 
 A memorial to the 9/11 firefighters, a garden in front of the station designed and donated by the Cayuga Heights Garden Club, is a peaceful reminder of the brave men and women who serve our country and our Village. (Public Sites)

This Gustav Stickley home was built for the Peer family. After Franklin Sherman Peer's death in 1922, his wife Harriet lived in the home with their son Sherman Peer, his wife Eleanor, and their two children. Sherman was an Ithaca lawyer active in village social and political affairs. He was best man for his friend Robert E. Treman, who married actress Irene Castle. The Tremans settled nearby at Greystone. Sherman, a 1906 Cornell grad, later served as Cornell provost for external affairs. 
 
 The original address of the Peer home was 401 Highland Road but later became known as 2 Parkway Place. It was the first Stickley home in Ithaca and clearly reflects the Craftsman style of architecture. It is one of three grand residences marking The Parkway and Highland Road corner at the entrance to Cayuga Heights, the other two being the house built by Jared Newman at 9 Parkway Place and 104 The Parkway, built by J.H. Tanner, the Village's first treasurer (see a photograph taken of the three homes in about 1916 in former village historian Carol Sisler's book, Enterprising Families). In 1949, Sherman Peer sold 2 Parkway Place to James and Diana Rothschild, who owned the popular Rothschild's Department Store downtown on the Ithaca Commons from the turn of the century until 1980. (Notable Architecture)
Home to architect LeRoy Burnham, as well as C. Tracey Stagg, New York State senator, and Maxie Baughan, professional football player. (Notable Architecture, Sports History)

Former home to chemist and Nobel Prize winner, Vincent duVigneaud. Also home to Thai Princess, Bajrakityabha, 2004, as well as to chemist Jack Raven Johnson. (Notable Architecture, Major Award Winner, Notable Women)

Home to Kenneth Greisen, Manhattan Project Scientist. Earlier in the century, home to American ornithologist Louis Agassiz Fuertes. Read more about Fuertes' role in Boy Scout Troop 4 along with Charles Newman (see 110 The Parkway), son of developer Jared Newman. As narrated by John Marcham, (see 112 Oak Hill Road), an active member in the 1950s, Charles was inspired to found the troop when he pulled aside Lord Baden Powell, the founder of Boy Scouting, for conversation during a visit the latter made to the Delta Upsilon fraternity house at Cornell in the company of Theodore Roosevelt. 
 
 In 1917, Scoutmaster Newman was called to serve in World War I and was replaced by a Cornell Heights neighbor, the renowned artist and naturalist Fuertes. With ready access to Cornell faculty and Fuertes as guide, the troop focused on nature study and took part in  such wartime efforts as selling savings stamps, Liberty Loan Drives, and the County War Chest.
 
Today, the troop is one of the oldest in the country. It currently meets at Cayuga Heights Elementary School.

The early history of student activism at Cornell, in the late 1950s, is associated with the history of this handsome 1929 brick, stone, and stucco house where Cornell President Deane Malott and his wife once lived.
 
 In 1958, Kirkpatrick Sale, who grew up at 309 The Parkway and went on to become a prolific author on environmentalism, politics, and other subjects, was a leader of a Cornell student protest outside the Malott's home. At issue was a university policy forbidding unchaperoned parties in off-campus housing, which the protestors thought was the "last straw" in attempted control over student life. Sale and his Cornell roommate, Richard Fariña, who fictionalized the era in his 1966 novel, Been Down So Long It Looks Like Up to Me, were part of the protest. Fariña's friend, Thomas Pynchon, described the scene at the house in the foreword to a later edition of the book. Such events as these set the stage, of course, for the much more serious student radicalism to come and were likely an impetus to move the next Cornell president farther north in the Village, away from the campus boundary. (Notable Architecture)

Architect: Clarence J. Swartwood; suggestions by Helen Binkerd Young

Former home of Robin Palmer, activist and member of the Weathermen (Students for a Democratic Society, SDS). Imprisoned at Attica State Prison. His family owned the land at Palmer Woods across the street, and they transferred it to the Cornell Plantations. (Notable Architecture)

Name: Gipfelruh
Notes:
Harriett Martin Libby (1881-1969) purchased the lot at 206 Overlook Road in 1909 from Cayuga Heights developers Charles and Louise Blood and Jared and Jane Newman. Originally from Brooklyn, Harriett Martin earned a master's degree in botany/horticulture in 1905 and a PhD in photography in 1910, both from Cornell. She and her husband Luther Libby (1882-1941) ran a farm in Caroline for many years. Between the 1930s and until she sold the property in 1953, Libby rented out rooms in the house at 206 Overlook. She also seems to have supplemented her income during the Depression by working out of the home as a “corsetiere,” or corset maker. Notable residents of the home include scientific illustrator Elizabeth Burckmyer and artist Christian Midjo. Burckmyer illustrated Liberty Hyde Bailey's "Garden of the Bellflowers," among many other works. One of Midjo's paintings can be seen at Marcham Hall.
(Notable Architecture; Notable Women, Artists)

Former home of historian and Pulitzer Prize winner, Michael Kammen and Tompkins County historian Carol Kammen, and earlier, Cayuga Heights Village Engineer Carl Crandall. (Major Award Winners, Writers, Notable Architecture)
Home to Trevor Cuykendall, Manhattan Project physicist, and physician and artist Muriel Cuykendall.

Architect Clinton L. Vivian designed this English Country Revival home at 209 Cayuga Heights Road for the Wanzer family. Elmer and Mabel Little Wanzer purchased the lot in 1927, and the house was constructed in 1928 by contractor Andrew H. McPherson. Elmer Wanzer, who lived in the home from 1928 until his death in 1933, owned the Wanzer Block at the corner of State Street and Aurora Street, where Viva Tacqueria is currently located. His father built the building and ran Wanzer and Howell Grocers there ​originally, and later Elmer took over the store. It appears the grocery store was closed following his death. Elmer also served as Village of Cayuga Heights Trustee from 1929 to 1933. (Notable Architecture, Entrepreneur, Village History)
Former home of Theodore Thoren, American Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame. (Sports History)

Name: Amanda Manning and Elijah LaBar Farmhouse
Notes:
In the early 1800s, Richard Manning cleared the land for a farm that would later become Savage Farm and then what we know as Kendal at Ithaca. The Manning Farm fell within lot 89 in the Township of Ulysses, the predecessor of the Town of Ithaca. After Richard's death, his wife Lydia Manning transferred part of her property to her daughter Amanda and son-in-law Elijah Labar for $300 in 1845. The deed stipulated that Lydia would receive $20 a year during her lifetime from the Labars. This is most likely the Labar house that farm neighbor Carrie Manning mentions in the diary that she kept in the year 1869.
  
 Carrie notes almost daily visits at the Labar house. Just about every evening her Pa “went over” to see fellow farmer Elijah Labar. Carrie also wrote with concern that Leroy Labar, Elijah and his second wife Caroline’s son, who was just a year older than Carrie, had scarlet fever and that Elijah’s older daughter Lydia was sick.
(Notable Architecture)

Name: Elmcote
Notes: Former home of Mario Einaudi, founding director of Cornell Center for International Studies, and son of second president of the Republic of Italy. House designed by neighbor and early woman architect, Helen Binkerd Young. (Notable Architecture, Notable Women, School Teacher)

World War I international correspondent and author Maude Radford Warren moved to Ithaca to be near her close friends, economist Herbert Davenport and his wife Harriet, who lived at 216 Overlook Road. She later had a home built at 416 Highland Road. Warren is buried at nearby Pleasant Grove Cemetery. (Notable Women)
From 1973-2005, this was the home of chemist Jerrold Meinwald, who won the National Medal of Science. Meinwald is also a noted flutist. (Major Award Winners)

This stucco home with low-hanging, open eaves and exposed timbers is typical of the Craftsman homes in the Cornell Heights Historic District. One hundred sixty six homes are part of a single historic district that straddles Cornell Heights (125 homes) and Cayuga Heights (41 homes), which together comprise what we now call the Cornell Heights Historic District. (Notable Architecture)
Home to Robert J. Kane, CU Director of Athletics (1940-1976), President of the US Olympic Committee (1977-1981), US Olympic Hall of Fame. (Major Award Winners, Sports History)

Name: Manning-LaBar Farm House
Notes:
The two-story red brick building now on Kendal at Ithaca property along North Triphammer Road is known as the Manning-Labar Farmhouse. According to former Cayuga Heights Village Historian Carol Sisler, the home was built sometime between 1810 and 1829.  It is a candidate for the oldest home in Cayuga Heights. 
The façade of the original part of the house is distinctively symmetrical, with two side-by-side front doors flanked by nine-over-six pane windows. It has a side gable that faces the road and a low-pitched roof with chimneys on each end of the house. A later addition extended the house to the west, maintaining the plain brick exterior but disrupting the Georgian symmetry. The foundation is brick, which is an atypical feature for Tompkins County, suggesting that the builder of the home drew on an architectural tradition from another region.
Beginning about 1811 the property was the “homestead” of Richard Manning (d. 1827) and Lydia Vaughan Manning (1778-1848). Richard Manning purchased 36 acres from Lydia’s father, Daniel Vaughan, a Revolutionary War veteran from Knowlton, New Jersey. The Mannings bought an additional 47 acres from William Kimple, also a Revolutionary War soldier from New Jersey.
Richard Manning died land-rich but in debt in 1827, and the estate was required to “sell or lease” some of the family’s 393 ½ acres to satisfy his debts. Lydia, however, remained living on the homestead farm “subject . . . to the widow’s right of dower in her lifetime.”  Richard and Lydia’s son, Daniel Van Manning, is shown as occupying the property on Tompkins County maps dated 1853 and 1866. 
The property passed down through several generations of the Manning family until it was sold to Elmer Savage (1884-1943) and Genevieve Savage in 1920. Elmer Savage was a Cornell professor of Animal Husbandry who was internationally known for developing feed standards for dairy cows. He operated a dairy farm on the former Manning farm and bred Guernsey cows. 
Cornell University purchased the lot in 1968, and in 1994 the Kendal retirement community bought the property. It is currently rented out to Kendal residents as a private home, with Kendal’s wine-making club using the basement.
(Notable Architecture)

Name: Kendal at Ithaca
Notes: Later residence of Dale Corson, Manhattan Project Scientist, Physicist, Cornell President; also, Hans Bethe, Manhattan Project physicist and Nobel Prize winner. (Public Sites; Major Award Winners)

Name: The Little House
Notes:
Originally an outbuilding of the Wyckoff Estate in Cornell Heights, the simple structure was called a "gymnasium" because of a dirt track that ran around the outside. Intended for fitness and sport for the leisured class, it was a hastily built structure. The small building was sold for financial reasons, and the Sheldons, who owned the former Bush farm, purchased it for son Ralph Sheldon and his wife Emily and their family. 
 
Cut in half with hand saws, this house was transported up Triphammer Road to number 901. Mrs. Sheldon was widowed after her husband died treating patients with influenza after World War I. So when someone wanted to buy the Triphammer property, she happily hired a tractor to move the house to East Upland Road, though it got stuck in the neighbor's mud on the way! (Notable Architecture, Garden)

The majestic Greek Revival farmhouse now at 304 Highgate Road was originally located in the Town of Caroline.  According to research by local historian Charles F. Mulks  (1837-1907), Henry K. Morrell built the home on his family's 500-acre farm in 1846. 
In 1933, Martin and Louise Catherwood purchased a large lot at the end of Highgate Road from Jared T. Newman and Jane E.W. Newman. The Catherwoods bought the "Morrell Mansion" and had it taken apart, moved, and rebuilt on their Highgate Road property. After the Highgate Section became a part of the Village of Cayuga Heights, Louise Catherwood, who had taught in Cornell's College of Home Economics, served as the first female trustee on the village board, from 1956 to 1959. (Village History, Notable Women, Notable Architecture)
One-time home of agriculture professor William A. Stocking, for whom Stocking Hall at Cornell is named.

Name: Jessup Field, Cornell University Athletic Fields
Bush Farm House
Notes:
John and Elizabeth Sharp purchased the property from the Benjamin Cradit estate in 1824, and the home was built a year later. Elizabeth Sharp sold the property to Charles S. And Maria Manning Bush in 1842. 
The Bush family was originally from Pennsylvania. John and Jane Bush migrated from Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania, to Lansing about 1804. They had twelve children. Their son Charles S. Bush (1798-1864), who was six years old when his family came to Lansing, later married Maria Manning in 1846. Their son, Charles A. Bush (1848-1899), inherited the farm. Developer Jared T. Newman bought the house and surrounding farmland and sold it in 1910-11 to the Sheldon family, who had moved to Ithaca from a farm near Lisle, New York, to take advantage of the excellent education Cornell offered their children. They later bought "The Little House"at 303 E. Upland Road for their son and his family. (Notable Architecture)

Name: Africana Studies and Research Center
Architect: Carl C. and Robert B. Tallman, Ithaca, NY
Notes: The Africana Studies and Research Center was established in 1969, in the aftermath of the student unrest at Cornell and against the backdrop of the Civil Rights Era. Suspected arson at the Center's initial building on Wait Avenue, following the '69 Willard Straight Hall takeover, convinced the University to provide a new one. Controversy over location ensued; some people, whether associated with the Center or not, considered its proposed placement on the north of campus--a twenty minute walk from central campus--a form of segregation. But 310 Triphammer was agreed upon, and the building includes an extensive library and classrooms. (Public Sites)
Residence (2004-15) of Pulitzer Prize winning historian Frederik Logevall . (Major Award Winners, Artist)

Name: Kappa Delta Rho
Notes: Public Site, Fraternity

Name: Northcote; Acacia Fraternity
Notes: A non-conformist himself, Henry Shaler Williams was likely influenced by the work non-conforming atchitect Frank Lloyd Wright when he had his long, horizontally oriented home built hugging the ground. Low ceilings inside provide a feeling of intimacy in an otherwise expansive design. (Public Sites, Fraternity, Notable Architecture)

Name: Lakeland Apartments
Notes: Home to chemist and Manhattan Project scientist Richard A. Reinhardt; as well as Paulus Pieter Bijlaard, to whom Queen Wilhelmina in 1941 conferred knighthood in the Order of the Netherlands Lions, the highest civil award of Holland. (Major Award Winners, Manhattan Project)
Home to John Hartell, American artist of first the Impressionist, and later the Modern Styles. One of Cornell University's Sibley Hall art galleries is named for Hartell.

Home of Edith Clifford Williams, non-conformist daughter of Henry Shaler Williams. Edith, known by choice as "Clifford," was an accomplished artist in Alfred Steiglitz's inner circle, and her work was featured in Marcel Duchamp's modernist journal Rongwrong. Williams used her inheritance from the sale of her parents' home, "Northcote" (now Acacia), to build this house. 
 
 When her parents disapproved of the man she wished to marry, she declared she would never marry, and she did not. Instead, she maintained a fifty-year affair with the influential Chinese intellectual, activist, and diplomat, Hu Shi. Their romance and detailed letters are captured in the book, A Pragmatist and His Free Spirit: the Half Century Romance of Hu Shi & Edith Clifford Williams.  (Notable Women, Notable Architecture)
Home to Harold Widom, (1960-68), American mathematician well known for his contributions to operator theory and random matrices.
One-time home to astronomer Carl Sagan, Pulitzer Prize winner and creator of the Emmy Award-winning series, Cosmos. (Major Award Winners, Notable Architecture)

Name: Pi Beta Phi
Notes: Public Site, Sorority
Residence (1963-72) of chemist and National Medal of Science recipient Jerrold Meinwald. (Major Award Winners)
Home to Gregory Vlastos, MacArthur Award winner. Also home to Pulitzer Prize-winning musician Karel Husa. (Major Award Winners)
Former home of Bruno Rossi (1940-45), physicist and Manhattan Project scientist. Ithaca City phone directories show his address as 400 The Parkway. (Major Award Winner)
Known as a "Fallingwater of Ithaca;" built by the son of Frank Lloyd Wright's Fallingwater builder. (Notable Architecture)

Name: Westview Apartments
Notes: Residence, in 1964, of MacArthur Award recipient A.R. Ammons. (Major Award Winners)
Notable Architecture
In 1958-1959, home of writer Vladimir Nabokov, author of Lolita and Pale Fire, among other books. (Notable Architecture)

This unusual home's architecture was influenced by a style employed by Frank Lloyd Wright in 1936. A variant of a Usonian home, such homes are distinguished by their small size and are generally single-story dwellings on inexpensive sites. A flat roof and natural lighting provided by clerestory windows provide a strong visual connection between the interior and exterior spaces. Designed and owned by Cornell architecture professor Alexander Kira, the home adheres to Miesian design principles. This minimalist aesthetic was evident in the two homes he designed for himself in Cayuga Heights (the other has since been replaced). Those who had occasion to visit recalled that he and his wife, Marian, were always proud to show off the many special features of these houses. Storage compartments were designed to accommodate specific items such as wine glasses, placemats, or socks. The interiors were always comfortable, clean, properly arranged and camera ready. (Notable Architecture)
Past residents include mathematicians Piergiorgio Odifreddi and Richard H. Rand. (Notable Architecture)
Former home of astronomer Thomas Gold, who is buried in nearby Pleasant Grove Cemetery in Cayuga Heights. (Major Award Winners)

World War I international correspondent and author Maude Radford Warren (1875-1934) moved to Ithaca to be near her best friend Harriet Davenport and her husband, economist Herbert Davenport, who lived at 216 Overlook Road. A popular writer of magazine stories and novels, Warren had one of her best-sellers, "The House of Youth" (1924), made into a movie by director Ralph Ince in 1925. Warren had this home built at 416 Highland Road to duplicate her former home in Chicago's Hyde Park neighborhood. Warren is buried at nearby Pleasant Grove Cemetery.Mathematician Ralph Agnew purchased the home from Warren's estate. (Notable Architecture, Notable Women, Writer)
Home to physicist and Manhattan Project scientist Joseph Levinger.
Residence (1966-68) of chemist Roald Hoffman, Nobel Prize and National Medal of Science winner. (Major Award Winners)

Name: Clovermere
Notes: Built for Cayuga Heights developer Jared T. Newman's family as a summer residence on the small lane between The Parkway and Highland Road, "Clovermere" was later winterized and moved to its current location in 1921. Newman began construction of a commanding new residence with Spanish and Mission style elements, including a red tile roof, near the entrance to Cayuga Heights at what is now 9 Parkway Place (originally 409 Highland Road). (Notable Architecture, Mayor of Ithaca, Village Hisotry)
Home of poet and MacArthur Award winner A.R. Ammons. Ammons is buried in Pleasant Grove Cemetery in Cayuga Heights. (Major Award Winners)
Home to mathematician and Manhattan Project scientist Paul Olum, as well as classical pianist Egon Petri  (Manhattan Project, Musicians)
In 1956-1957, home of writer Vladimir Nabokov, author of Lolita and Pale Fire, among other books.

Notes: Co-ed Chemistry Fraternity, Public Sites

Name: Alpha Epsilon Phi
Notes: Sorority, Public Sites
Former home of John Kirkwood, chemist and physicist. (Major Award Winners)

Address: 501 Highland Rd, now known as 100 Iroquois Road
Full Address: 501 Highland Rd, now known as 100 Iroquois Road, Ithaca, NY 14850
Notes: Home of Ruth Durand Sawyer, Newbery Award winning children's author, and her husband, eye doctor Albert Durand. It is one of Cayuga Heights' all-concrete houses, supposedly so constructed because of the fear of fire of Ruth Durand's mother-in-law, who lived with them. (Major Award Winners)
Home (1985-1992) of Henry Louis Gates, Jr., MacArthur Award and Emmy Award winner. (Major Award Winners)
Home, in 1949, of physicist, Nobel Prize winner, and Manhattan Project scientist Richard Feynman. (Major Award Winners)
Home to George Charles Embody, ornithologist and author of the Birds of Madison County.
Home to Wolfgang Fuchs, mathematician specializing in complex analysis and is known for the Erdős–Fuchs theorem.
Home of Charles H. Blood, developer of Cayuga Heights. (Village History, Notable Architecture)

Name: Broadlawns
Notes:
Home of builder Jes Dall, Jr. Dall built many J. Lakin Baldridge-designed homes. They were architecture students together at Cornell. A large oak tree is noted in the original specifications for the house and still stands today. It is likely over 300 years old. Inside the home is a wooden built-in ironing board inscribed on the bottom in pencil and reads "J. Dall, F(?). Dall, March 9, 7:45 PM, 1933." Below that, in children's handwriting,
 it says "Christmas is coming. Santa Claus is coming too." (Notable Architecture)

Name: Broadlawns
Notes: Built for Franklin C. Cornell, Jr., and his wife, Cordelia Hearne Cornell. (Notable Architecture)
1951 home of James Sumner, chemist and Nobel Prize winner. (Major Award Winners)
Home of Charles Blood, co-developer of Cayuga Heights. (Village History, Notable Architecture)

Name: Alpha Chi Omega
Notes: Public Sites, Sorority

Name: Thorn Hill/Robin Hill
Architect: J. Lakin Baldridge, Edward Lawson - landscape architect
Notes:
Current home of Cornell's president. Renamed in 1944 for the house that Soames Forsyte built for beautiful Irene in The Forsyte Saga, Robin Hill was originally known as Thorn Hill, and architect J. Lakin Baldridge designed and built it for his family. In 1944, the Baldridges sold the mansion to Robert E. and Carolyn S. Treman, who bestowed the current name on the home. In 1963, the university purchased the house, and Cornell President James Perkins and family moved in. The change of the president's residence from 205 Oak Hill Road may have been occasioned by the university administration's wish to move farther from campus, out of easy reach by students, given an incident at the 205 Oak Hill address in 1958.
 
 The half-timbered house is built of locally quarried Llenroc (Cornell spelled backwards) stone and stucco, with leaded glass windows, large and small slate roof tiles, and copper water pipes, indicating the high-quality standards used. A monument to the pre-Depression era, the house boasts 9,000 square feet, has seventeen rooms, nine fireplaces, eight bathrooms, and closets as large as entire rooms. 
 (Notable Architecture)

Also owned by artist Edith Clifford Williams, this home has a stucco exterior similar to her residence at the corner of Highland and Kline roads. The house was later a residence to artist Christian Midjo. One of his pieces graces the walls of Marcham Hall (836 Hanshaw Rd.) Also home to other creative residents, including poet Deborah Tall and husband-and-wife pianists. (Writers, Musicians)
Built by the son of Frank Lloyd Wright's Fallingwater builder, in the vein of Fallingwater. (Notable Architecture)

Home of M.H. Abrams, known for The Norton Anthology of English Literature. The story of student unrest at Cornell picks up from the late 1950s protest at President Malott's house at 205 Oak Hill Road and moves on to the handsome house with the beautiful west-facing porch that runs the length of the home. During the trying days of prolonged and sometimes violent demonstrations at Cornell in 1969, Abrams hosted Cornell faculty gatherings on this porch to discuss the turbulence and the university's options. (Notable Architecture)

One-time residence of musicologist and jazz authority Marshall W. Stearns. He was known for his New York City radio programs and television show. In 1956 he accompanied the Dizzy Gillespie Band on a tour of the Near East on behalf of the U.S. Department of State. This was also a residence of Jerrold Meinwald, chemist and National Medal of Science recipient. (Major Award Winners, Notable Architecture)
Residence of Lyman Parratt (1946-94), physicist and Manhattan Project scientist.
Residence (1947-49) of physicist and Manhattan Project scientist Phillip Morrison. (Major Award Winners)

In 1906, Charles W. and Margaret Williams purchased the lot at 515 Highland Road from developers Jared Newman and Charles Blood. The Greek Revival house was finished the following year. Charles Williams had come to Ithaca in 1905 as the division freight agent for the Lehigh Valley Railroad. He later established the Williams Electric Company. In 1942, the Williams’ niece, Dorothy Knight Knox Holden, sold the house to Edward R. and Bergljot Audhild Sanne Martinez Ybor. Edward was the grandson of Vicente Martinez Ybor, the Cigar King of Ybor City, Florida. The Ybors renovated the home in 1946. For the garden, Norwegian-born Audhild Sanne designed a "Little Europe" of stone bridges and castles in the backyard, which she had a Cornell engineering student and stone mason construct. The structures, which were built from reclaimed stone from a downtown building that had been torn down, reminded her of Europe. (Notable Architecture)
One-time home of architect Carl C. Tallman.
Built by architect, Conway L. Todd, he was the first resident here. In the 1950s this was the site of a dance school, Dean School of Dancing.
Notable Architecture

Architect:
Carl C. Tallman, Architect;
K. Gorton Davis and Edward Lawson, Landscape Architects
Notes:
Electrical engineer Paul M. Lincoln (1870-1944) hired architect Carl Tallman to build this grand seven-bedroom, four-bath home "of the English type." In 1901, Lincoln had invented the synchroscope, a key piece of equipment for electric companies that is still in use today. The widowed Lincoln moved to Ithaca in 1923, after he was named director of Cornell's electrical engineering department. His daughters Elizabeth Hague Lincoln (Cornell '27) and Helen Hague Lincoln (AB, Wellesley, '21, Cornell graduate courses, 1923-1924) both attended Cornell. Nearing retirement from Cornell, Lincoln founded Ithaca's Therm-Electric Meters Company in 1937 to market electric demand meters that he held patents for. Elizabeth Lincoln married Harrison Goodman, who was a founding director of Therm. The Goodmans lived at the home with Lincoln until 1942. 

Notable Architecture; Technological Innovation

Clarence and Wilhelmina Morse purchased the J. Lakin Baldridge-designed Tudor Revival home from builder Jes Dall Jr. in 1925. Clarence was the grandson of Ben Morse, one of the founders of the Morse Chain Company.
(Notable Architecture)

Carriage house residence and laboratory (1944-69) of Robert Virgil Morse, of the Morse Chain family. He developed a "dive bombing sight" that helped turn the tide of World War II. (Notable Architecture)
Former home of Amy S. Treman, of the Treman family, and her husband, Thomas E. Milliman; Also home to Sanford S. Atwood, Cornell dean and provost, and later president of Emory University.
School Teacher
Home (1973-91) of physicist and Nobel Prize winner David Lee. (Major Award Winners)
Home (1967-86) of poet and MacArthur Award winner A.R. Ammons. Ammons is buried in Pleasant Grove Cemetery in Cayuga Heights. (Major Award Winners)
Home of biochemist and Nobel Prize winner James Sumner. (Major Award Winners)

Novelist Pearl S. Buck lived in the second-floor apartment of this home in 1932, the year she received the Pulitzer Prize for her book, The Good Earth. Buck later received the Nobel Prize as well. The following year, her husband, John L. Buck, is listed as resident. However, it is unclear whether they lived here at that time or in China. (Major Award Winners, Notable Architecture, Notable Women)
In 1951-1952, home of writer Vladimir Nabokov, author of Lolita and Pale Fire, among other books.
Notable Architecture

Name: Far Horizons
Notes: Notable Architecture
Home (1942-1951) to physicist, Nobel Prize and National Medal of Science recipient Peter Debye. Debye is buried in nearby Pleasant Grove Cemetery in Cayuga Heights. (Major Award Winners)
Residence (2002-07) of Michal Lipson, electrical engineer specializing in photonics and MacArthur Award winner. (Major Award Winners)

Name: Palmer Woods
Notes: Land transferred by E. Laurence and Katherine Palmer of Oak Hill Road, who lived across the street. In the 1930s, neighborhood children used to play "Capture the Flag" here. (Public Sites, Natural Environment)

Name: Hanshaw Farmhouse
Notes: The Savage Farmhouse is a handsome four rooms over four rooms design.The house's name came from Elmer and Genevieve Savage, who owned the property from 1919 to 1947. Richard Manning and Catherine Kline Manning lived on the lot in the 1860s and 1870s. Richard was a Civil War veteran and was a corporal in New York's 34th Regiment of Infantry, which fought battles in Virginia and Maryland, including the Battle of Antietam in September 1862. He is buried in nearby Pleasant Grove Cemetery in Cayuga Heights. Jared Newman developed the Highgate area on the site of the Troy Farm beginning just beyond the current location of this house, in 1922, hoping it would later become part of Cayuga Heights, which it did. (Notable Architecture)
Former residence (1951) of physicist Paul Flory, winner of the Nobel Prize and the National Medal of Science. (Major Award Winners)
Home (1949-51) to chemist Paul Flory, Nobel Prize and National Medal of Science recipient. (Major Award Winners)
One-time residence of composer Steven Stucky, Pulitzer Prize winner. (Major Award Winner)
Home to physicist Richard M. Diamond, who worked on the "Gammasphere" and won the Bonner Prize.
Home to physicist and Manhattan Project scientist Stirling Colgate (of the Colgate toothpaste family). He co-founded the Santa Fe Institute. (Manhattan Project)

In 1955-56, home of writer Vladimir Nabokov, author of Lolita and Pale Fire, among other books. Possibly rented from school teacher Ruth Fisher. Also one-time home of World Food Prize recipient Robert Chandler. (Notable Architecture, Major Award Winner)

Minimal Traditional homes such as the one at 825 Hanshaw Road exemplify the inexpensive small houses prevalent across the United States during the Depression, the war years, and the postwar period. Built as part of the “Small House Movement,” these compact single-family homes had a simple layout—usually consisting of just two or three bedrooms, one bathroom, a kitchen, and a living room on a single level. Newspapers and magazines published plans for small homes that could be built quickly and affordably with standardized materials. (Notable Architecture)

Name: Formerly Kline Farmhouse, "Bedbug House"
Notes:
What happened after the sale of the old Manning Farm by Franklin C. Cornell to his sister Eunice and her husband Charles Taylor in 1919 is the story of what we know today as the Warren Real Estate building (with Tompkins Financial Corporation as its current tenant) at Community Corners. It was originally the farmhouse of the Kline family. Philip (1781-1874) and Elizabeth Winters (1787-1854) Kline migrated from New Jersey to Tompkins County by 1817. In that year they purchased 42.67 acres in Military Lot 90 from John Sharpe. After Benjamin Cradit’s death in 1823, the Klines bought part of the Cradit lands north of their original lot. The red brick Kline farmhouse was built on the former Cradit lands.
 
Eunice and Charles acquired the Kline farmhouse with the purchase of the Manning Farm from brother Franklin. They bought cows and ran a dairy business, which was not a great success. Widowed and without funds, Eunice was cared for by the farm manager and his wife. She died in 1942; the house was inhabited by a series of residents, thereby acquiring its infamous name, "Bedbug House." A cement garden, called "The Mall" was built in 1928 for the Taylors. Some of us may remember the house as the Peggy Cornwall women's clothing shop before Warren Real Estate moved in and accomplished renovations to the Federal style facade. (Notable Architecture)

Name: Marcham Hall; The Stone House; Stonecroft
Notes:
Known as Stonecroft, this stone house was built for Dorothy Cornell, a granddaughter of Ezra Cornell. Dorothy's sister and brother-in-law, Eunice C. and Charles Taylor, lived next door at 830 Hanshaw. The home featured a slate roof, a chandelier or two from New York City's Hotel Martinique, a picket fence imported from France, fine ironwork hinges and handles on the doors and windows, a greenhouse, and a charming sun dial on the outside wall. The house changed hands many times after Dorothy lost her money in the Great Depression.
 
 In 1969 the Village purchased the house from the adjacent Village Green Shopping Center, naming it after Cornell professor and former Village mayor Frederick Marcham (112 Oak Hill Road), who served from 1956 to 1987. (Gardens, Notable Architecture, Public Sites, Notable Women)
Home of Charles Treman, Jr., relative of developer of Cayuga Heights. (Notable Architecture, Village History)
In 1957-58, the home of writer Vladimir Nabokov, author of Lolita and Pale Fire, among other books.
Notable Architecture
In the mid-1980s, this home was purchased by H.M. Hassan II, King of Morocco.

Name: Corners Community Center
Notes:
Built in the late-1940s, the original Corners Community Center, a small but distinctive, colonnaded white building with a (formerly) red gable roof reminiscent of a Colonial-era tavern, is a Village landmark. Designed to serve the daily retail needs of Cayuga Heights residents, it continues to be the only shopping center at the hub of any neighborhood in Ithaca.
 
 Incorporated in 1946 by Walter C. Heasley, Jr., Gerald A. Hill, Henry J. Shirey, and Charles E. Treman, Jr., it was an outgrowth of Newman and Blood's original planning for small shops that would be within walking distance of villagers' homes. As such, its future is important and receives attention in the Village Comprehensive Plan. 
 
 In the 1950s, John Kangas owned the Corners Barber Shop (which still welcomes customers today), and Sophia Brand owned the Corners Beauty Shop. Today the Corners hosts businesses representative of today's tastes, such as Island Health and Fitness gym. 
 
 It is also said that Vladimir Nabokov spent time at Corners Community Center and even included it as a setting in his book, Pale Fire. 
 
 (Public Sites, Village History, Shopping)

Home (1938-1976) of writer Morris Bishop and artist Alison Mason Kingsbury. Alison worked on the murals at Radio City Music Hall in New York City and was recruited to paint the frescos on the walls of Cornell's Willard Straight Hall Student Union in 1925. She is thought to have helped bring Vladimir Nabokov to Cornell. (Notable Architecture, Notable Women)

Name: Gas Station
Notes: Public sites, Shopping
Home of chemist Paul Flory, National Medal of Science and Nobel Prize winner,. (Major Award Winners)
Home to American mathematician Burton Wadsworth Jones, known for his work on quadratic forms. (Notable Architecture)
One-time residence of physicist Robert Wilson, Manhattan Project scientist, winner of the National Medal of Science, and architect of The Fermilab. (Major Award Winners)
One-time home to architect and noted playground designer Robert Leathers. (Interesting & Offbeat)

Former home of William M. Woodward, physicist and Manhattan Project scientist. Also residence of physics lab engineer Alfred Sarant, member of the Rosenberg spy ring. He was friendly with Phillip Morrison, Hans Bethe, Richard Feynman, and other Manhattan Project scientists at Cornell, though they did not know of his nefarious connections or activity. He fled to Mexico with his neighbor, Carol Dayton, the wife of a close friend, two days after Julius Rosenberg's arrest.

Name: Sunset Park
Notes:
Constructed on the slope of a sandbank by developer Jared Newman on what he called the "Western Slope." Providing panoramic views of Cayuga Lake and the City of Ithaca in the valley below, Newman and his wife Jane donated the parkland to the Village in 1928 with the stipulation that the view would never be obstructed. 
 
 Sunset Park is a prime spot for Ithacans to view the July 4th fireworks over Cayuga Lake.
(Public Sites, Natural Environment)

Name: Purple Sculpture
Architect: Richard Evans 2nd III, Cornell University, Johnson Museum of Art
Notes: Sculpture, Public Sites, artist

Name: Original Slate Sidewalk
Notes: Near 106 Oak Hill Place, a plaque marks the original slate sidewalk installed by developer Jared T. Newman. (Village History)

This half-timbered stucco house with a slate roof was built by John F. Daley, a real estate developer and builder, for George and Alvena Dale. George Dale was a Cornell professor of Romance Literature from 1925 to 1954.
(Notable Architecture)
